<h4>Rules of Poker</h4>
<div class="helpText">
<p>
Have you played Poker before? It's fun! There are many variations of the game. This one is called Five Card Draw. You and the computer both get five cards to start with. You look them over and decide which you'd like to keep and which you'd like to discard. After your discard, each of the discarded cards are replaced and you compare your hand to the computer's and see whose is higher.
</p>
<p>
The table below shows the rankings of the hands. The higher up the table, the higher the rank. If you and the computer have the same hand, it looks to see who has the highest cards. So if you have a flush with an Ace, that will beat a flush whose high card is a Jack. If you have pairs, three of a kind, or four of a kind, it checks in the matched cards first. If those are the same, then the additional cards are checked to see which is higher. Every now and then you and the computer might have the exact same cards. Then it's a tie! That's wild! It doesn't happen often. I ran about 5,000 simulation games when I was building this site, in fact, and it never happened. But it could! If it happens to you, you must be lucky!
</p>
<p>
In case you're wondering how you know which card is higher, I'll explain! The number cards, 2-10, have the value listed on their face. Jacks are worth 11, Queens are worth 12 and Kings are worth 13. Aces are a little different. They can be worth 1 or 14, depending on the rest of your hand. Usually, you'll want them to be worth 14. But, for example, if you have Ace, 2, 3, 4 and 5, you'd want the Ace to be worth 1. You'll have a straight. That's a pretty good hand.
</p>
